Republican strategy to counter Obama’s re-election
The Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to combat electoral fraud.
The Brennan Centre considers the latter a myth, claiming that electoral fraud is more rare in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
Republican lawyers have reported only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively influence the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will in part undermine the U.S. democratic system.
Unlike in Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the U.S.
It was in this spirit that a majority of U.S. governments enacted new laws from 2009 that made the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon grew wide after the November 2010 elections, which added 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states were introduced during the year 2011 alone.
New electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
Moreover, these laws also reduce pre-voting periods, invalidate the right to register as voters on the day of the poll and withdraw citizens with a judicial file their right to vote.
Prior to the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to place such a demand.
In 2008, the Supreme Court of the United States confirmed the constitutionality of the Indiana law.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have been sponsoring bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo ID cards issued by a government agency in their state.
Moreover, five million new voters in 2012 did not have such an identity card.
However, it often costs more than a hundred dollars to obtain the required ID card.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000; 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have the required photo ID card.
Much more.
Students, voters considered to vote more for Democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their photo ID issued by their institution.
On the other hand, these same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use to vote on the cards issued by these clubs.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to present such a demand.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are American citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Hispanic vote.
Two out of three Hispanic voters are in favour of the Democratic Party.
In 2011, Republican legislators sponsored laws abolishing voter registration on the day of the poll in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequence.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns contributed to recording about 10 million citizens.
However, measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the rate of enrollment of new voters by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have passed laws in five other states to reduce the pre-voting period.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African-Americans, while the latter accounted for only 13% of the state’s voters.
The same was the case with Hispanic people.
These represented only 11% of the voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In return, whites who made up 76% of the voters represented only 46% of the voters voting in advance.
Of course, Democratic legislators and their supporters strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by the Democratic governors’ vetos.
The U.S. Attorney General intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to limit the damage in part.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed legislation requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
Nevertheless, the new rules in place will undoubtedly make the exercise of the right to vote more difficult in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the supportiveness of the laws that have been voted and see it as an obvious goal to influence results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Centre report shows that the states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes required by the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively influence the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will in part undermine the U.S. democratic system.
Prostate cancer screening: passing the test or not?
Indeed, the APS test would sometimes show erroneous results, with false negative or even false positive results, which result in unnecessary medical interventions.
What makes men already reluctant to pass screening tests even more hesitant.
Passing the test or not?
We asked for the advice of two specialists.
In studies conducted in the United States, there was a lot of contamination among the control groups, so it is difficult to interpret these data and have strong recommendations.
Another study, the European one, concluded that there was a difference in mortality between patients who had a screening and those who did not.
This study also showed, with follow-up after 12 years, that you are between 30 and 40% more likely to have metastases if you are not screened.
So I recommend the test from the age of 50, or from the age of 40 if you have a direct parent who has already had prostate cancer.
Men of African American origin are also at greater risk.
The key is to make the right decision once we have detected cancer.
There are aggressive cancers and others that are indolent.
The patient must really understand the degree of risk of his or her cancer, by offering him or her possible options, by not necessarily treating prostate cancers that do not impair long-term life, and instead opting, in these cases, for active monitoring of the disease.
Today, many men who detect cancer will not be treated because their cancer is not aggressive and does not threaten their lives.
We're going to suggest that they do active monitoring and if the disease progresses, we're going to offer them treatment.
Increasingly, criteria are being precisely determined to decide who should or should not be treated.
I recommend passing the test.
