Higgs's Boson Shedding
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson created a whole emotion last summer, and for reason.
Indeed, it is believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the Universe, just that.
And then, it is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or "less worse" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely sure that it is the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of doubt that we hold an authentic new particle, and that it resembles much the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Furthermore, new data unveiled this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto seems to confirm this, but there is still lack of data to be absolutely certain.
Anyway, let's assume it's the Higgs, since the chances of being wrong seem small, and let's see what it's about.
There is, in this lower world, a fatally indispensable law that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
No way to break this rule - and don't try too hard, you're going to hurt yourself.
Even though particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has such a law: the principle of exclusion of Pauli, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consisting largely of some of their characteristics.
From there, physicists classify particles into two categories.
In one corner there are good citizens named Fermions, who wisely obey Pauli’s principle.
And on the other hand there are the bosons, a dirty gang of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least not for this principle, which means that they can actually be in the same place, at the same time.
These bosons are then divided into two groups, according to the site (absolutely extraordinary, by the way) The Particle Adventure, of the Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not approach here, and the "particles of force", by which the great forces of nature spread and to which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, we must emphasize here, are not all as exotic beasts as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "light particle" that is the "messenger" of electromagnetic force.
When, indeed, a particle with an electrical charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disturbs" the electromagnetic field at this specific location, a bit like a rock thrown into a pond.
From this "disruption" arises an electromagnetic wave (from light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore, one of the "force-carrying" bosons.
More stable field
The same goes for the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which must be "disturbed" for this boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it is necessary to reach very, very high energies, somewhat as if it were a frozen pond whose only a very large rock could ride the surface.
That's why it takes an immense particle accelerator like that of CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a 27-kilometre ring! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is once again useful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
It is not all particles or materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold itself on a fridge.
And in the same way, it is not all particles that interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the others (like the photon, yours) do not have a mass.
Now, what can "bring" all this research, asks Ms. Plamondon?
For science, this is used to verify the validity of the Standard Model (MS), and this also allows physicists to examine any gap between the observations and predictions of the MS.
Moreover, there are many who want to be found, because any difference could open a door to a "new physics" and close some holes in the Model.
This one, it must be said, still has enormous shortcomings, offering no explanation for gravity (oups!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the Universe (re-oups!).
But we haven’t found such differences at CERN until now.
Impacts
The repercussions of these researches in the daily life of Mr. and Madame Tout-le-Monde are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will be no.
At the very beginning of the 1960s, the pioneers of laser in the Bell Laboratories did not suspect the revolution that their work would trigger.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed), in 1962 - initially the laser was rather seen as a "lab gadget".
Imagine...
And then, applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the research.
For example, this same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his optical work.
This sensor, although it was not at all its original intention, now serves as an "eye" to all digital cameras in the world, and earned it the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
Of course, this doesn’t mean that LHC’s activities will necessarily transform our lives, but that means that, really, you never know...
Palliative Care - The Best Way to Die... <0x7C> The Duty
With its Commission dying in dignity, Quebec recently debated the delicate question of the end of life.
The debate should be resumed soon as a bill is being prepared.
