The Duty tried to take a closer look at it.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that swallowed him had left him a two-year rest.
"They gave me five years to live, I was seven years old," he said, lying in his bed at the palliative care home Victor-Gadbois of Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for it," he said.
The disease does its work: an enormous weakness that prevents him from going to the toilet alone, and even eating alone.
Attacked in front of an appetizing lunch, he agrees to let himself eat help, resigned.
Courageous, he even gets to smile, talks to strangers who take care of him, bring his medicines, offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is that I should be healed from diarrhea, it's humiliating," he said.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this disease.
“During our lives, we learn that a man pisses standing,” says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois house.
Regressing to the child's stage, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
"It depends on the person's ability to accept regression," he notes.
For, in the opinion of several people working in palliative care, great moments take place at the very heart of this regression.
Patients who enter the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home are all suffering from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this point, the team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provide so-called "curative" care.
For Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is to die "consciously and suffocated."
But the disease made me discover my children.
“I have good kids,” she adds.
“I no longer have any wishes in life,” she said, before accepting a mask to help her breathe.
In the coming days, she is waiting for a last visit from her son who came from Italy.
In Victor-Gadbois, a group of volunteers provide body care and food assistance.
These are palliative care, given when there is nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is a palliative care bed for 11,700 inhabitants.
It's very little when you know that you all end up dying one day.
Here, life continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the house’s doctors.
Whether it’s physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
When dying, we will accept to provide mouth care to the brandy or Pepsi, as requested.
Diabetics will no longer be required to control their sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night, we served a beer to Mr. X, who died overnight.
This morning, his son will finish the beer at the feet of the deceased.
“We help loved ones as much as patients,” says Nathalie Savard, Director of Care.
At the Victor-Gadbois house, the days follow but don’t look the same.
Alongside a 93-year-old man who enjoys his last family assembly in the courtyard, well stuck in his pillows while he is drinking in his honour, a 36-year-old young man dies tragically, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children, after trying everything to survive.
“For six months, there have always been three to five beds that are occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45,” worries Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home arrive from their homes, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77 per cent of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient reaches the terminal phase of his or her life, whether at home, in the hospital or in the nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois house and the Grand Montréal Palliative Home Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in the care offered to cancer patients.
It is precisely this great deficiency in Quebec health care that causes several palliative care doctors to fear the adoption of a law on euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by palliative care committees including Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to testify to their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not efficient enough to ensure that everyone will be entitled to quality palliative care before euthanasia is agreed.
Recently, she said, I saw a patient spend 14 days at the emergency, in great pain, without doing the necessary to relieve her.
I'm afraid that patients are only asking to die because they don't get adequate care.
And at the same time, several oncologists are stuck with their patients until the last day, despite the worst forecasts.
Helen Richard's survival expectations were already minimal when she gave up harsh chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she replied that she regretted that I stopped fighting.
Yet she told me I was over!
Not Almighty Care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank caregivers for not acceding to their request after they were relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Society of Palliative Home Care of Greater Montreal, patients would be resistant to pain treatment in 8% of cases.
At the end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which means to sleep the patient until the moment of his death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can no longer pretend to not hear that part of the suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelieved patient will have the opportunity to have this palliative sedation.
Those who are not relieved always say the same phrase: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to euthanasia me,” that means “I want to be relieved.”
