With Bitcoin, pay and sell without banks
The opposite of current central bank-based currency exchanges, identified transactions and processing fees between stakeholders.
In addition, as often in these technologies, a political vision is palpable: the conviction that the current monetary system, made by banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible in dollars, euros...) and a secure exchange protocol in the way of BitTorrent, which allows peer-to-peer file exchange.
Approximately 200,000 transactions have already been recorded through 15,000 computers on the network.
A small thousand websites accept bitcoins as donations or as a means of payment.
The price of bitcoin, after reaching a peak of $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to $2 five months later, before returning today around a dozen dollars (prices are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Nothing very impressive compared to global exchanges in real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) was interested in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes bitcoin as “the most successful virtual currency,” “in competition with the dollar or the euro” and “similar to conventional currencies.”
Bitcoin stands out from other types of virtual currency such as "credits", used to advance in a video game that you earn by playing or that you can buy (and sometimes trade in return).
The social network Facebook has also developed this type of system.
But each time, a central authority monitors and processes trade.
With Bitcoin, all the nodes on the network are both account book depositaries, auditors, currency issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two email addresses in the way of an email.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically by a dual-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins exist in the public book of accounts, distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched to computers, and whose winner, sort of a provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding this additional line.
This is a phase of file hashing, i.e. transforming a large file into a shorter and unique fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before "hacking" the whole.
The goal is to find the number that gives a particular footprint (many zeroes at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other knots easily verify that it is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any change would change the footprint.
If, to fraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remaining orphaned because both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the challenge won 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided in two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to one hundred millionth, leaving margin.
The difficulty of the challenge is also seen with each increase in computational power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
Websites providing services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins in deposits stolen.
“The fault used does not concern the protocol itself,” says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real-world payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this default.
Prominent actors like Wikipedia refuse donations of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the book of accounts and showed that nearly 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, “giant sales” were launched.
“Threety thousand dollars have been traded,” said Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, who converts bitcoins to gold.
Pierre Noizat, also author of a teaching book on this currency, believes greatly in the potential of this technology as a network of transactions.
His system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which come back cheaper.
The bearer also manages his identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement in merchants, who do not need to install new terminals or software.
It is enough for them to provide an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize," says Pierre Noizat, who assures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general movement to challenge hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
“It will take time for Bitcoin to push forward, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicted.
The ECB, in its report, plans to reassess the various risks, now considered high, if this currency succeeds.
We left Afghanistan.
