A constitution with forceps in Egypt
This is another poker shot by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants it full powers, it has decided to play his va-all.
Taking everyone short, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State had granted two more months to this House to finish its work.
It has been nearly two years since Egypt relied on a provisional text, repeatedly amended which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal imbroglios.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the President persists in his "autocratic delusion," continuing to "traiting his word" and "pieds down law".
On the side of its supporters, it is assured that this is a way of ending the institutional and political crisis as soon as possible, by accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be held within fifteen days.
A very short period of time that requires the Brothers to give up their plan to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy as protests are raging across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote favorably, as he said in an interview with the U.S. weekly Time.
The ultimatum to the Egyptian people is: "Either you vote for my text, or I retain full powers", which are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this constituent Assembly, a vast Islamist majority, voted on the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals were missing the appeal.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they knocked the door, saying they could not have made their views stand.
The same had been done by representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, replacing members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Not surprisingly, it is most often unanimously that the articles were voted.
Commentators also enjoyed the fact that one of the only differences of the day was expressed around... the time of prayer, some members of the committee felt that the constituent's pendulum was poorly settled.
The text, which was still being voted last night, contains 234 articles.
Object of all attention, article 2 remains ultimately identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stipulating that "the principles of sharia are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a major demand, hoped to be able to replace "principles" with "rules", which would have allowed for a stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a proof of their goodwill and respect for other components of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," replied the Liberals, who see it only a blow of communication.
In their view, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They include section 220, which confers on Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular with regard to verifying the compliance of laws with Sharia.
According to Egyptian specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "the people called to pronounce are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
We can see the first fruits of a theocracy.”
The fears of the Liberals are further aroused by the fact that the next rector of this university should be much less moderate than the current one.
"For now, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulemas but academics, for some trained in the French system," said Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges "that there may be ambiguity around Article 220, because the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
It refers to the "fiqh" in particular [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And in the future, the question might arise to what extent civil judges are competent to rule on it."
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is highly criticized because of the extensive powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another controversial point is the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the military's wish, the review of the Defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
No more will civilian trials be prohibited in military courts, as required by human rights associations.
The latter also express their concerns about the text, which they consider liberticide.
The offence of blasphemy is maintained and insult is now banned, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, including the press.
Furthermore, no article echoes the protection of women anymore, says Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive is the prohibition of torture by article 36.
The word was not included in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to speak last night on television, demonstrations are planned this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the World Centre and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land brings together the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort and a wild nature.
Argoumenty i Fakty has selected five great reasons to visit Israel.
Go worship the holy places
Return to the shores of the Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that anyone who enters these “baptism backgrounds” will be touched by divine grace.
As for Galilee, it is the land of the miracles of Jesus: where the water was turned into wine, where Jesus walked on the water, where he calmed the storm, or where the fishing was miraculous.
This is where Jesus appeared before His disciples after the Resurrection.
But where you will find the most holy places, it is in Jerusalem.
The believers travel the street of suffering or the path of the Cross (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
This path begins near the Antonia Fortress (the pretory), where the trial took place, then led through the streets of the old town to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on the Golgotha, to the place of Crucifixion, then to that of the Anointed Stone and tomb.
This is where the Christian center of the world is located, a symbol of the salvation of humanity.
According to Christian legend, the Cross Monastery is erected at the place where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified grew up.
Jerusalem also houses the most sacred place of the Jews: the Wall of Lamentations, which constitutes the remainder of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 BC.
According to tradition, people of different confessions leave small words accompanied by prayers that are then heard.
Traveling in height
Visit the ruins of Massada Fortress, an ancient refuge against enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 BC for his family.
These ruins are located on the steep rocks of a mountain at 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineering enthusiasts can get there by their own means.
For others, a cable car takes them to this full of history summit.
In the north of the country, between 1,600 and 2,040 m altitude, is the Mont Hermont ski resort, which welcomes many tourists in the winter.
A shuttle can take you there from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are a total of 45 km long.
Old beliefs want pagan gods to live on the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
This country houses nearly 300 museums.
It is not possible to visit all of them during a single stay.
Here are the five most interesting ones that are really worth the tour.
First: the Museum of Israel located near the Knesset (Parliament).
It houses the very ancient Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea manuscripts, discovered in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as nearly 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
Also see: Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
The paintings of the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso are mainly exhibited.
In Acre, Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths composed of the moldings of the visitors and supervisors of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the unique private Ralli Museum where you can admire Rodin's sculptures.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Entrance is free and donations are prohibited.
The fifth museum is the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem Memorial, located in Tel Aviv, which returns to the most dramatic historical pages in history.
The most tragic part is the children’s memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter and enter into total darkness.
Stars shine.
Then you hear the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health and well-being
The three major resorts of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, Red Sea and Dead Sea.
Each has swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, as the temperature of the water does not fall below 21° while the temperature of the air can reach 23°.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can swim in it all year round.
By the way, it is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point on Earth, 417 m below sea level.
Azure water contains brine and very easily retains swimmers, even those who do not know how to swim.
The landscapes that surround it are of surreal beauty.
It comes to carry out a treatment based on salt water, lemon, healing sludge and to treat various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes but also to simply relax.
Discover the secrets of ancient times
They are kept by the old town of Tel Aviv, Jaffa, on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris that connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it is here that Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life here.
Tourists particularly like to walk through the narrow alleys that bear the name of the zodiac signs.
It is said that if you touch the street walls corresponding to "your" sign, fate will smile to you.
In Jaffa you will be able to meet newlyweds who came to take photo sessions from all over Israel and even from other countries.
In Caesarea, King Herod's city, you can stroll through the Roman theatre, "conquer" the crusaders' fortress.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera shows.
Note to tourists
If you are going to Israel, don’t worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer dollars to the euro, as they are easily exchangeable in shekels (today 1 dollar is equivalent to 3.8 shekels).
For urban transport, these are mainly buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the country's only metro line, composed of six stations and capable of connecting the lower and upper parts of the city.
It is almost an underground funicular.
The ride in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1h30.
In Israel, the Jewish tradition wants to celebrate the Sabbath on Saturday.
From Friday evening to Sunset on Saturday, markets, shops and public transportation cease their activity.
And the working week begins on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels serve only kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, scale-free fish and dishes composed of both milk and meat.
It offers a multitude of dishes based on lamb and beef, soups and desserts based on coconut milk but also hummus, traditional Jewish dough, different sauces, ground chicken peas balls, falafels, fruits and vegetables.
There are no wandering dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many well-fed cats that walk around as proud air.
You can see them sleeping at night on the roofs of parked cars.
These cats love passing places and don't refuse to be eaten.
The rental of a car varies depending on the brand from $37 for 24h (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 a day.
Renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
An entrance to the museum costs on average 30 shekels.
The language of numbers
Three million tourists from around the world visited Israel in 2012.
These were mostly people who came to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 miles of Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land from January to October 2012, 51% more than in 2010, prior to the cancellation of visas on February 9, 2011.
"Who has language, go to Moscow": migrants save money to learn the language
As MEPs and human rights activists argue about what the mandatory language testing law will give, fraudsters selling “fake” certificates have already appeared in the country
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the time they are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to make money to help their families stay at home.
Since December 1, a law has entered into force and stipulates that every migrant worker will have to pass a Russian exam.
At present, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the services, housing, private services and retail sectors.
However, over time, the Federal Immigration Service promises, testing will become mandatory for all immigrants.
Furthermore, the knowledge of the language, but also that of the history of Russia and the foundations of law will need to be validated.
You will need to validate your language knowledge in Russian to obtain and renew your work permit.
Exempted are only nationals of countries where Russian has official language status.
Persons who have obtained certificates or educational diplomas before the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also not affected by this Act.
Benefit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of exam centers will be under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of Russian Language, the University of the Friendship of Peoples, the State University of Moscow, St. Petersburg State University and other higher education institutions in Russia.
Immigrants will be able to pass exams in all cities of the country: more than 160 centers have already been opened throughout the territory.
This initiative to introduce reviews was supported by Members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But, before the law comes into force, human rights defenders have already repeatedly asked the question in the press: what is it going to do?
What will the obligation to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First, replies the representatives of the immigration service, this will reduce the number of people suffering "from slavery to work".
Many are talking about defending the rights of migrant workers, explains the director of the office of the Russian Federal Migration Service in Tajikistan, Victor Sebelev.
The protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will 90% solve the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise for unprofessional, untrained migrants, those who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without understanding of the language, Sebelev certifies, the future migrant is meant to meet dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "travel" in an overcrowded house where he and dozens of his fellow men will be tormented for months without food and paper and will have to trim between 12 and 14 hours a day.
We are receiving many complaints from our migrants.
"In them, one thing is promised, and when they arrive, they are deceived, they are taken their passports, and they do not get the planned salary," confirms the head of the Tajikistan Migration Service Works Branch, Tolib Charipov.
Don't argue with me, Mr. Policeman!
However, many citizens of Central Asian republics who wish to come to Russia to make money confide not only in not knowing the language of the country they wish to visit, but also in writing with difficulty in their own language.
Of course it is not their fault, but their misfortune: few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to take even a passable primary education.
Indeed, their families don’t even have what to feed their children, let alone dress them properly and equip them for school.
As soon as they come to adolescence, these young people leave to earn money as soon as the opportunity comes.
It’s hard when you don’t know the language, they trust.
"You feel decreased and decreased."
However, human rights defenders note an important aspect of the language law.
The exams will only be for migrants who have legal status.
Without status, there will be no examination or official work thereafter.
However, most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or Defense to Enter"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason? The administrative barriers and still these linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: between 12 and 16 miles of rubles.
And then, you can get a fake registration quickly for only 1,500 rubles.
Russian police know that we have fake documents, that we have no records, hence cases of extortion.
"They are asking us for 100, 200 rubles, what to buy cigarettes, tea," Tajikistan's national Oumed Khushkadamov told reporters.
“Get quick, don’t let go and buy yourself a beautiful work of art.”
On the first day of the entry into force of the Language Act, it was found that migrant registration papers were not the only ones that were false.
Several false language examination certificates have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Service.
Counterfeit papers come out of an ordinary color printer.
Of course, their new owners didn’t take them for nothing: every migrant who so hoped to facilitate the task of exams had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
It is twice and a half more expensive than the official procedure: it will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Power representatives and human rights defenders agree that the short-term goal is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these “paper boxes”.
The authorities may give migrant workers who have not been able to validate the first-stroke examination time to take language classes.
In addition, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve active communicating with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not deal with the arms market
The share of crimes involving legal weapons is very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior proposes to tighten the law against civilian weapons holders.
This is the reaction of the authorities to recent incidents, whether it be the shootings at marriages or the killings organized by Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, who killed seven people.
Police want to prohibit wearing rubber bullet weapons in public places and raise the legal age for obtaining the gun license from 18 to 21 years.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma committee for security and anti-corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that the amendments to the arms law would be introduced to the State Duma soon.
Not everyone is pleased to see that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "screwing the screw".
An open letter appeared on the Net, in which its authors, representatives of various shooting centers, demanded to abandon “this insane hardening.”
The percentage of crimes committed with a registered weapon is minimal, Vasiliy Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime specialist for the BBC, told Russian service.
According to statistics from the Ministry of the Interior, over a six-month period in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a gun registered in police services, while 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded over the same period.
The authors of the open letter are confident that strengthening civilian weapons laws will not prevent criminals from supplying themselves to the black market.
According to them, today we can find any weapon in Moscow for a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior states that it controls the dissemination of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from factory to officer
The black arms market is supplied via several channels.
The main channels are five, says Victor Baranets, a retired colonel who served ten years at the Ministry of Education and the Headquarters.
Screenshot taken from a site taking arms commands
The first is the "military trace", i.e. weapons that were stolen during military operations in the Caucasus.
"These weapons were stolen by the Russian officers, but also by the Caucasians," Baranets said.
The second type of weapons from the black market are those stolen by criminals from law enforcement.
Baranets explains that these are both weapons stolen from police stocks and weapons stolen directly from law enforcement officials.
The illegal guns go on sale from the military warehouses.
Many of them have often experienced explosions.
"Verified versions indicate that some fires were triggered purposely to conceal the deficit," the former military said.
For Baranets, weapons manufacturers are for something.
“We see private weapons factories that do not compete with competition on the international market and sell weapons on the black market, especially in Moscow,” says an expert.
One of the other sources of the black market is smuggling.
A significant share of guns and machine guns comes from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
“We find a local production, sometimes artisanal, a mafia has formed and organizes the procurement,” the former military added.
Where did the weapons come from?
Experts assessed the approximate share of each source of illegal weapons on the black market.
A report on the issue was prepared in 2011 by the Center for Problem Analysis and Study for Public Administration.
Experts analyzed the Ministry of Interior and Rosstat reports, criminal records and public data on weapons portals.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, the researchers explain, come from the military and law enforcement.
Half of the weapons on the black market were found there “because of employees whose work is related to weapons,” the report explains.
According to the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from places of military conflict, 14% are stolen at the time of manufacture, and 5% come from “clandestine searches.”
A vendor and consultant of an armory that asked to keep anonymity assures that for a long time no one has bought the weapons found by these clandestine search specialists; they are too old.
Most often, he says, sellers will search for new goods in military warehouses.
The person buys through a sign a unit, for example a TT gun.
It is handed over to him by passing the goods through a wire grid.
"He transports it to the city and resells it for €900 per unit with two chargers," he says.
"It is true that the police are aware of all the cases, so when crimes are about to be clarified, they make a check purchase from illegal weapons dealers," he added.
"As in a luxury shop"
The seller and buyer are usually found through knowledge.
I visited websites, blogs, until a guy manifested and offered me to come to the Begovaya station where someone became taking me into a "coin" to trade.
The price of the gun was given to me on the spot.
Victor Baranets as a military observer
To find a gun, I need to know someone who has a contact, explains the seller. I know someone, but I don't trust him.
There are sellers in the markets, but there we must also come and say, for example, "On the part of such a person, who asked me to pass on that his daughter has lost a tooth."
Now I’m even buying a pair of American fists with the help of someone I trust.
He only hands them over to me because he knows I won't give it.
The young people are looking for weapons in different ways.
Former military Victor Baranets tried himself as a buyer of illegal weapons in the mid-1990s as he was preparing to publish an article on the subject.
The schemes, according to him, have not changed.
He was given a photo album in which he had "everything we want."
"I thought I was in a luxury shop," the military recalls.
There is no secret for the buyer, explains Baranets, we can try everything.
As a potential customer, I'm not just buying, we go with the seller in the forest and we set up a target.
"I'm being allowed to shoot and when I'm convinced that the weapon works well, we start negotiating," the expert describes.
A shop from his couch
Search engines display sites and groups on Vkontakte where weapons can be purchased "for different uses".
For this, we don’t need any documents and no one to meet.
“It’s enough to have a precise amount of money,” it was written in an advertisement on the website “Buy a gun or a fighting mitrail.”
Users leave their requests and ask their questions.
Are we selling to miners?
"Unpermitted, of course," asks the user "Ivan" (preserved spelling).
"Buy TT. Moscow", writes "Fedorenkov" in his very direct request.
The Federal Security Service has disseminated a huge network of fake sites and picks up people wishing to purchase fighting weapons.
