In recent days, a wave of protests has risen against the low wages practiced by Walmart supermarkets and famous fast food chains such as McDonald's, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy's and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
At the moment, no one can predict whether this wave will grow larger or fade quickly.
These actions are supported by trade unions and a number of leftist associations.
Alongside the modest increases in wages received by basic employees at Walmart and in fast food chains, the organizers of the demonstrations want the creation of trade unions.
This sector is not currently covered by the trade union movement.
46 cents a year?
The protests began last week, after Thanksgiving, the "Black Friday", as a floating rain of balances seizing millions of inhabitants fell on America and sometimes triggered splash.
On that day, some employees at Walmart, which employs 2.2 million people worldwide, left their positions to organize strike pickets with unions and left-wing activists in the company’s stores whose products are intended for consumers of the modest and medium-sized classes.
Walmart markets everything from diapers to hunting rifles to car batteries, vacuums, eggs and milk.
Products are on average 8% to 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That’s why many poorly paid employees at Walmart are shopping only at their workplace.
The price and selection of products made Walmart one of the most powerful groups in the United States.
According to critics, Walmart can afford to sell its products inexpensively because of the low salaries of its employees.
The latter also complain about difficult working conditions, for example the lack of forklifts or portable scanners.
Participants in the "Black Friday" protests demanded a salary increase, complaining that the price of medical insurance provided by the company had increased from $30 to $100 per month.
For the basic employee at Walmart who gets $9.5 per hour, it’s a sum he can’t afford.
Scientists at Berkley University in California show that if Walmart increased the average wage to $12 per hour, it would cost the group $3.2 billion.
This is 1.1 percent more than it is currently spending.
If Walmart transferred all the increased wages to consumers’ shoulders, each race in the store would be 46 cents more.
In just one year, they will spend $12.39 more than now.
Walmart supporters note with satisfaction that the protests took place in only nine states and caused no harm to the group.
The "Black Friday" continued in stores from 8am in the evening to midnight the next day and Walmart sold over this period 5000 items per second.
His cash registers totalled 100 million transactions for "Black Friday".
Spokesman Dan Fogleman said in an interview with the left-wing Huffington Post that "less than five" Walmart employees had left their positions and that the protest was just a "com-operation among many others" on the part of the organizing union.
"Next customer!"
The protests continued this week in New York and also concerned Walmart stores (in this progressive city they are not much appreciated, which is why they are not yet installed there) but McDonald's and other cheap restaurants.
McDonald’s announces selling billions of servings and then they don’t even give you sick leave and don’t pay you for the work you’ve done honestly!
