Fast-foods increase them over time, but on average, its core employees reach $8.90 per hour in New York.
No one touches less than them in this town.
It is unimaginable for me to live with that money in New York.
There was a time when nearly a quarter of American teenagers worked at McDonald's after high school while living with their parents.
Few people saw their primary source of income or wanted to stay there for a long time.
Today, I find myself interviewing McDonald's employees who complain about having to live with that salary and sometimes having to feed their children with it.
On the other hand, on the Wall Street Journal forum there are comments saying it is irresponsible to have children if you don’t know what you’re going to feed them with.
Protesters who launched the move on Thursday at 6:30 p.m. near McDonald's on 40th Street and on Madison Avenue demanded that cashiers and cooks of fast food be paid at least $15 an hour, more than twice the current minimum wage.
They also called for the creation of unions in the fast food sector.
U.S. law prohibits the administration from preventing and punishing union protesters by harassment or dismissals.
