Recently, fans of new technologies have become used to perceiving augmented reality through special glasses.
Initially, it was Google that unveiled its current model this summer at its annual conference and in November it was learned that Microsoft had applied for the patent.
However, the interview with the director of the interactive 3D technology group at the Microsoft laboratory in Cambridge, Shahram Izadi, shows that for the company’s scientists, the glasses are already ancient history.
They are tempted by the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with bare hands, by creating open virtual spaces.
- Could you tell us in a few words what your research group is doing?
- We are working on the interaction between man and machine and we are trying at the same time to broaden the boundaries of this interaction.
Humanity as a whole has for the moment remained at the pixels on a flat screen and sometimes at the touch.
We want to look 5 to 10 years ahead and guess the radical changes that will occur with this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are a step forward, and almost no Xbox is sold today without Kinect because everyone is interested in ordering by gesture.
- What does the future also hold for us?
- Although the Kinect has rendered physical interaction, a lot of things happen on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
Information entry has been improved (the system receives more data), but performance, for now, is not really.
We’re trying to change that and we’re working on truly 3D imaging systems that work on different technologies, including projection technologies.
We need to bring the computer world out into ours, into the physical world, make it more tactile.
For this, however, it is necessary to identify not only the user, but also the space that surrounds them.
Thus, we will be able to complete the real world with virtual objects in a more practical form.
And for starters, let’s get rid of these stupid virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think of voice control?
It is appreciated, but is it not overestimated?
It cannot be said that it is the panacea: the question of confidentiality arises because one does not always want to inform others of their actions or intentions.
In fact, every type of interaction with the computer is good, but each in its niche.
For example, to control the devices in public places, we had a project for which we thought we had gestures, not broad gestures, but rather discrete, narrow gestures.
The gestures were not captured by the camera of the apparatus, but by a hand-worn bracelet that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is currently large, but it is theoretically possible to reduce it to the size of a watch.
In fact, the future will be marked by the mixed command, for example: gesture + voice.
- What do you mean?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass that can?
You would do it with words and gestures.
- Usually, I'm just talking.
- Oh, it's gonna be hard to recognize.
- So you want to force users to adapt based on what the machine can or does not do at any given time?
- Not necessarily, but this is a mutual reconciliation.
I think that very soon we will have to work on developing new types of sensors that will allow us to better identify human reactions.
These can be laser sensors, for example, they produce a fairly good resolution in depth and this is very important.
- If you are interested in your work on Xbox Kinect sensors, what do you dislike in modern cameras?
Do they lack resolution, depth or anything else?
- In principle, it is on the current generation that we rely on our work on 3D recognition.
It would obviously be good to get about 8 megapixels at a speed of 1000 c/s.
But the problem is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
Compared to this latter point, all current technologies are fairly good, this adds work to algorithm designers.
It is important to keep in mind the resolution of X and Y axes, but also Z.
Speed also matters a lot, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic, and 30 c/s really aren’t enough, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche of our Redmond laboratory gave the touch of the sensors a regular processing delay between 1 and 100 μs, the current sensors being closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands how much this influences the interaction of man and machine.
I would need a device like this in my work, but it doesn't need to touch, to have more frames in the second.
Shouldn’t the number of cameras be increased?
- The Kinect now has three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second, a reflected signal receiver.
And the third camera is actually a usual sensor of the visible field.
It is not used to define the depth of the object.
A lot of cameras could solve this problem.
Or worsen it by increasing the required volume of calculations.
It would be interesting to create a soft product similar to the Kinect, play with the camera curve and see how it could help set locations.
