Giving birth in space
The Earth is in danger.
Global warming or collision with a murderous asteroid.
Caravans of space shuttles with Earthmen on board are heading out in search of a rescue planet.
To save humanity, a big question arises: how can we continue to live our species in weight or on a rescue planet?
I don't think there's a lot of choice.
There are actually two real planets that can be conquered, even if only by hypothesis.
"These are Venus and Mars," says Vladimir Sourdine, a researcher at the State Astronomical Institute P.K. Chternberg (GAICh).
If on Mars the conditions are more suitable for life, the temperature at the surface of Venus is 500.
We can only live there at very high altitude or on the orbit of Venus... in space.
We began to focus on issues of reproduction in space by focusing on flora.
Half a century ago, there were experiments on plants.
Four generations of peas grown in orbit did not differ in any way from Earth varieties.
Then we put insects, small reproductive drosophilic flies, into orbit.
In 1979, cod eggs were sent into space to see how a weighty embryo was developing.
At the exit we get a quite normal chicken.
Then the problems start.
"The problem is that the chick has to find support, it has to get on its legs and start moving," explains Vladimir Sychev, director of the laboratory of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences (IMBP).
With no support, the chicks agitated in a disorderly manner.
And after 10 hours, newborns saw their instincts completely atrophy.
The chickens did not react to light or sound.
Unfortunately, they would simply die after four days.
“We stabbed their eyes twice, then gave up, because it is simply impossible to work with them there,” says Vladimir Sychev, noting the failure of experimenting with chicks in space.
The latest biological "miniature arch" with animals was sent into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in the spring of 2013.
However, the biosatellite " Bion " will only ship species of the same sex.
There was an experiment with rats sent with their fetus into space.
In principle, nothing supernatural has been discovered.
"They were still biosatellites, and then this is the only experiment, and we need to do this kind of research," notes Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, the rats of space gave birth to their offspring.
Nevertheless, it is not yet possible to perform reproductions directly in space.
It's not a thin affair.
By losing their usual environment, animals are no longer able to realize their sexual instincts.
Unlike animals, man is capable of doing so in principle.
The Homo sapiens possesses abstract thinking, it is capable of creating a suitable emotional background.
This type of experiment is not carried out for ethical reasons.
Women have been in space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was taken by Terechkova.
And the female body is what humanity has most valuable.
Our moss flew and no one on Earth could tell if it would stand after a flight into space.
If she could have given birth to a child after the flight.
"No one was answering this question," explains Vakhtang Vatchnadzé, a retiree from the rocket and space sector.
In June 1964, just a year after her flight into space, the first female cosmonaut Valentina Terechkova gave birth to a little girl.
The child's father, Andrian Nikolaev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second female cosmonaut Svetlana Savitskaya, after being twice in orbit and even working in an extra-vehicular environment, gave birth to a son.
However, the risk remains.
We have few, even very few cosmonauts who have had nothing and give birth to a healthy offspring after long flights.
"And if they are longer, it presents a danger even during orbit flights," concludes the pilot and cosmonaut, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of Russia, Valeriy Poliakov.
