The head of the ISC (Superior Institution for the Control of Public Finance) said: "The control of self-employed work (in Czech " Švarc system ") has failed because of politicians.
In the field of public procurement, the Czech Republic has competent inspectors and quality legislation, but is lagging behind with regard to its application.
This is what Miloslav Kala, Vice President of the Superior Institution for the Control of Public Finance, said in an interview with Aktuálně.cz.
"The law will never be perfect, but its application must be fair and, in my opinion, that is what is missing from us," Kala said in his commentary on the current situation.
A joint check conducted by Czech and German inspectors also suggests similar findings.
As an example of abusive practice, he cited Petr Nečas' approach to the "Švarc system".
Mr. Prime Minister recently stated that the SDG is not going to bother entrepreneurs with controls; is it allowed or prohibited?
“The law must be enforced in one way or another, so if it prohibits something, even the head of government cannot prevent an authority in charge of going to inspect demanding compliance with the law,” Kala notes.
At the meeting of the supervisory committee in the House of Deputies, you mentioned a Czech-German draft in which the public procurement legislation of these two countries was compared.
What was it about in concrete terms?
This is a parallel check that we launched about two years ago.
Simply put, EU legislation provides for managing public procurement and specific national legislation, as well as a practice itself, which follows it.
We have gathered all of this together and although this control procedure has not yet been completed, there are very interesting differences that appear to us: generally speaking, our legislation is perhaps "stronger and better quality", however, according to some parameters, the practice as such is better in Germany.
This therefore confirms that it is not sufficient to develop more and more detailed rules on an ongoing basis, but that it is necessary to focus on the very implementation of the law.
How can this project help you concretely and what does it result for you?
Common control of this kind should contribute precisely to the fact that we stop striving to clarify laws, to lower and improve thresholds, when this does not have a really positive effect.
The principle of good management means getting the thing in question at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest), in order to exclude any enrichment and possible criminal activity.
But by lowering the market thresholds, this goal will not necessarily be achieved.
It may be that this system is so overwhelmed by paperwork that those looking for the faults will find much more opportunities than if the threshold had remained higher.
You are talking about internal issues regarding the implementation of public procurement legislation.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there a similar institution to our ISC or a different mode of organization?
As for the institutions, similarly to the ISC, there operates the Bundesrechnungshof which is organized similarly, it also has a council constituted a little differently, but these two institutions do basically similarly.
The competences are also, to some extent, similar, but with a nuance in relation to our system: Germany is a federal structure, so it also has such accounts at the level of the various Länder.
The BRH can only control federal money, which corresponds to our state resources.
The public funds managed by our regions and municipalities are controlled there at the level of the Länder's accounts.
As far as national legislation is concerned, is it easier than ours?
I would not like to make a general comparison without concrete data, however, in some areas, Germany is often referred to as a model, but it can certainly not be said to do better in all areas.
Maybe it's because they have better detectives?
No, surely not, but I repeat, I don't have comparison data.
However, it must also be said that this country, which we see as a model, also faces a whole series of problems.
Otherwise they would have no advantage in cooperating with our institution, would they?
As for national legislation, what has meant for you, as an institution, the amendment to the Public Procurement Act, are its effects already felt?
Since this amendment entered into force relatively recently, it has yet to have an impact on our control operations.
As we do checks a posteriori, we have to count with a certain delay.
Our observations are currently only about the process of preparing for future controls - we have launched a new "risk detection of mismanagement" instrument with which we have screened nearly 14,000 public procurement - these changes will of course be felt, because the thresholds have been changed as well as the conditions for certain types of tender procedures and so on.
So do you consider the adoption of this law rather as an advantage or an extra burden for the administration?
I think this law is a step in the right direction and I hope that the future will confirm it.
The problem that can arise is that these rules are becoming more stringent and that it is not possible to comply with them.
Already under the regime of previous regulations, the claimant (e.g. the regional council, in the case of regional operational programmes) forced the controlled subjects to accept that any breach of the market law means a breach of budgetary discipline.
Is it really useful to make the law more stringent in this way?
No, not that way, I think.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or abuse the system but not punish those who make formal mistakes without consequence on the decision-making process.
Such a system will put greater pressure on the administration.
So what is the solution to get out of it?
Let's look where we're not going.
Recently, the Prime Minister stated that the SDG was not going to bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called Švarc system - what does it mean?
Is the Švarc system prohibited or authorized?
The law must be enforced in one way or another, so if it prohibits something, even the head of government cannot prevent an authority from acting in charge of inspecting and demanding compliance with the law.
He may declare, "We will change the law and allow it," but he cannot say that we will act as if nothing was.
The Contracts Act has relatively strict rules on the formalities to be fulfilled, precisely to protect the tender.
But it is also tragic that a bidder is eliminated solely because of formal defects.
