Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the Ministers of the European Space Agency countries, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency and is the second member state of the former Eastern Bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had started close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and over the years that followed participated in a number of ESA projects.
The road from Poland to space, however, began much earlier.
Already before World War II, passionate Poles were working on space flights; they did not always encounter understanding.
I would like to refer, for example, to A. Šternfeld's conference at the Astronomical Observatory in Warsaw, on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas drawn from his avant-garde work entitled " Introduction to Astronautical Science " .
The developments of this young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold and years later Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won in France the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize for his book "Introduction to the Astronautics".
The said Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in the Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a propagator of world-renowned astronauts, his contribution was rewarded in particular by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters of the hidden face of the Moon.
As early as 1925 a drain was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also unclear whether the rocket should be used to propel or brake the drain.
The only known information about this drain is that of the press at the time.
From 1933 onwards, the Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was conducted by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustav Mokrzyckiego.
The documents preserved show that this research had reached the stage of testing.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search was interrupted.
In 1937, the plans of a photoelectric fighter rocket, drawn by the engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the use of rocket technology were led by the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its operations.
After the war, other works devoted to aeronautics were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish astronautical society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, there is a company in the November 1954 issue of the newspaper Problem, in which there are four more detailed articles devoted to aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor Mr. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to the astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had a future.
At the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) deployed efforts to enter the International Astronautical Federation (created in 1951) and in the autumn, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice president of the International Astronaut Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the meteorological rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 meters was 80 cm long and weighed just under 5 kg.
Subsequently an improved version, RM-1A was built and, during the summer of 1959, flight tests of the RM-2 two-stage rocket were started in the Bledov Desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The next prototype should have been able to perform concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have had a range of up to 14.5 km and served to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962-1965, succeeded the first RM-type rockets.
This rocket, designed with two stages, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they distinguished themselves by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space with a volume of 0.4 litres, while in Meteor-1B it was 0.34 litres and in Meteor-1C was 0.62 litres.
The maximum range of all these types of machinery was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is still worth mentioning Poland's entry into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos program, Poland also participated in space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, the pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this program.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the Public Works Act.
This decision has raised a vivid debate in the public opinion.
It is undoubtedly interesting to consider this issue from a broader point of view.
Economic systems oriented towards liberalism, both in the EU and in the context of globalization, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
This concretely means that the different economic entities as well as national economic systems are constantly in conflict with each other.
This results from the principle of freedom of trade and the free (without limits) movement of private capital combined with limited financial speculation.
The considerable differences in labour price (wage) generate tension on prices.
The following meaning should be put under this term: a producer strives by importing low-cost goods to withstand economic competition by "making the competitor's price more expensive" in order to remove a greater share of the market and thus increase its own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either transferring production abroad, buying at low prices or disappearing, resulting in high unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and thus no responsibility for the unemployment it creates, the social burdens of the State necessarily increase.
This whole situation intensifies the perfect evil will of gentlemen and entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus compensate for the economic and social damage caused to the whole of society by this race for profit.
This situation is so publicly known that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistical data.
