The number of these people is already counted by millions.
As part of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, it becomes quite common for employees to receive such wages that the state is forced to pay a supplement to achieve the vital minimum.
Such a scandal has been updated, for example, in the case of employees working as auxiliaries in the federal parliament.
The economic measures of virtually all southern EU Member States generate, without a doubt, a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced either to emigrate (as was the case in the nineteenth century) or to live with wages of misery, on the margins of society, in the hope that their country will emigrate.
