The whole of power does not come from the people, as the Western constitution declares, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is clear that liberal democracies are now rapidly confronted with the situation described by Appianos in his book entitled "The crisis of the Roman Empire at the time of Caesar and Pompeius": "The state has long been in full depletion and functions were attributed by violence.
Bribes, favors obtained illegally, and stones and swords were also used to obtain these posts.
The under-table and corruption proliferated without limits and the people went to the elections with votes already sold" ... "Honest people didn't seek at all to obtain offices, it resulted once the state had absolutely changed mind eight months without consuls." ... "We really began to say that the remedy for this difficult situation was an autocracy and that it was necessary to choose a man."
In conclusion, as in ancient times, today's society is based on preference for personal profit, regardless of the interest of society as a whole.
In essence, private capital is no longer capable of understanding and enforcing the interests of society as a whole.
As a result, today as in the past, a decline without preceding elites, without any effort to carry out in-depth reforms.
