The film Argo: When everything goes wrong, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of demonstrators composed of Islamist students assaulted the U.S. embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, which had supported his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer the U.S. administration a positive outcome, it could not, indeed, abandon the Shah, because it would have severely shaken the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to obtain the release of hostages.
It was a tough blow for the US prestige, further exacerbated later by the fiasco of the attempt to liberate hostages by force.
The abducted diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate sparked in the United States a wave of solidarity and an anti-Iranian feeling.
The Iranian debacle contributed heavily to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo, by actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered a small victory to America.
Just before it was occupied, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After complicated circumstances, they met at the residence of the Ambassador of Canada.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran with a rocambolesque coverage: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a shooting team coming to make spots for shooting a big science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan of exfiltration expert Tony Mendez requires the collaboration of Hollywood.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized stores reported on this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictional production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, the film being based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
This is a part of a political thriller designed in a realistic way but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful blow, a betrayal - as, for example, in the trilogy Ocean's eleven, twelve and thirteen.
The atmospheres follow one another: documentary-style Tehran sequences (in the subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the era of events and how, thanks to these photos, these same situations were retranscrit in the film, there are no great differences),
lighter Hollywood passages, treated with irony and a bit of exaggeration,
and then scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the corridors and on the phone...
Ben Affleck has succeeded in remarkably starting his career.
As a ridiculed actor, he became a respected director and his play as an actor stopped arousing ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the dark policeman "Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The town" (2010).
This is also Affleck's first film not taking place in his hometown, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed his first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of the atmosphere in Argo, where the role of Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place on the streets, when reconstructing real facts; the initial sequence of the embassy fall is impressive by its clarity which also suggests the confusion and unpredictability occurring when suddenly, in a given place, a story page is written.
Affleck and his collaborators obtain a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the false shooting team in Tehran’s bazaar).
Too many actions in too many places
The director had to content himself with a subject offering in fact few exciting scenes, in the cinematographic sense of the term.
It is doing well, sometimes it adds some elements to the reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is ruled out by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the landing track is quite pulled by the hair).
Argo's weakness lies in its dissipated character, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
While it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood cooperators, their characters would have deserved a bigger place and they are not, far from, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of dramatic tension, he lets himself be seen with moderate interest, appreciating the realization and retro style of the 1970s.
He trains the spectator, but with difficulty.
