The architects of the MVRDV firm prove that true adventures are not just a matter of imagination. To convince yourself, just look at Spijkenisse and the newly erected mountain of books - 2 photos
“I think this building is funny, it’s very futuristic, finally something interesting to see,” Lisette Verhaig, a passenger on the lower side of the street, told us.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist at a large neighboring company, tells us, "Yes, this building is really beautiful."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has the internet, an iPad and e-books.
Nowadays, no one willingly goes to one of these crazy libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleeping town that has nothing attractive at the gates of Rotterdam, holds a rather special record.
The municipality of 80,000 souls has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to restore a few neurons to the brains, the city decided, a few years ago, to contribute to the general culture and to reproduce the seven fictional bridges that appear on the euro banknotes in the form of pretty small miniatures of painted armed concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
Thus the city authorities realized that there was only one way to take over the statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas, from the Rotterdam MVRDV Architects Office, bold master of stick diagrams and creator of mindful and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with his usual phlegm and presented himself to the competition in 2003 with five books under the arm and a laughing on the face.
And while the jury members still looked at each other, confused and shaking their shoulders, Maas, the madman, stacked his books of choice by order of size to make it a pyramid, and ended his speech supported by an activist argument: "Common dear!"
Here is my proposal for the mountain of books of Spijkenisse, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the €30 million mountain burst from the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and a few buildings and townhouses for a total of 50 houses.
In early November, the mountain of books received the second award "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus this dull little town, which to this day had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and a town hall of amazing uglyness, whose white façades suggest that they house a dairy, has enriched itself with a contemporary architectural work.
The most important thing is that Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Way to Reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under a cheese bell.
Sure, an elevator takes you to the heart of the massif, but the real joys of reading and architecture open to you when you step down the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The interior entirely made of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and elegant street lights unequivocally speak the language of municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We are already looking for public benches, dogs and little boys and girls who play the ball.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
"Normally, the library shelves are located along the facade and in the middle there is a large, dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal," says Willy Maas.
We completely upset the classic spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain of books has been well designed: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental center and the building’s technical center.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes paintings, sometimes balustrades, sometimes stair ramps.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even hardened building architects and engineers do not want unknown materials.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” says Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
This is how one day we found an ad hoc waste from agriculture in an agricultural company.
In the Netherlands, synthetic membrane of one millimeter thickness has been used for years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and we're saving time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be thrown away.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates of a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the effect of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and turns into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, whose smell evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
After almost 500 meters, the literary café offers a stunning view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and ficus in pots.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they mainly contribute to maintaining the ideal level of humidity of the literary mountain air.
Gifts for the New Soul
“It’s incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in terms of ecology,” says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is adjusted by geothermal.
Although the mountain of books lies beneath a glass bell, the sun illuminates little time inside, even in the days of good weather.
The thick wooden beams cross-mounted relative to the glass facade serve as a sunscreen, intercepting much of the rays.
The atmosphere is very pleasant.
Fully automated blinds take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned Septic computer scientist, has already risked entering the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even described the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "finally found soul."
Indeed, a few weeks ago, at the inauguration, every citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure has helped fill the gaps of the library that was not yet fully filled (today it has 70,000 books).
The concept is a success.
The rays are overflowing from all sides.
For architect Winy Maas, "there is nothing worse than a half empty library."
"I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between each citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's just for decoration."
This is how MVRDV achieved the master discipline called, in the professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse wrote a new page of literary history.
Even though she may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, this is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "The Germans must play a greater role."
Germany decided to abstain in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-EU relations, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the request of Palestinians to obtain observer status with the United Nations.
But then she decided to abstain.
- Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis did in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious because it has special relations with Israel.
But I also think it does not support the US position either.
Germany wanted to affirm its independence, but was not too critical of Israel.
During the March 2011 Libyan insurrection, Germany also voted to abstain in the vote on the establishment of an air exclusion zone.
At the end of the day, NATO imposed this measure.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is revising its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so to speak defined by the Americans and to introduce a German foreign policy.
Furthermore, the lack of coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans are confronted on several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still tapping to find this role, but they are on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
Foreign policy, as in France or Britain
What does the term "normal" foreign policy mean for the Germans?
It shows the willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national dossiers.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, that is, by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are to some extent different from those of other great powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position on the conflict in the Middle East and abstention in the United Nations vote?
Germany first has significant opportunities in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to hit the public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a decisive element.
However, I would not attach too much importance to it, because it is not an exclusively unilateral relationship.
But this is at least a decisive element in German strategic reflections.
Does Germany harm its relations with the United States by choosing to abstain in major votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think the Europeans and the Americans understand the German position perfectly.
That is why I think the fracture is not as serious as it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will be more respected.
Indeed, Germany has demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, the views on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
On the other hand, the United States announced its veto with a clear voice.
Does the opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama administration secretly shows a great understanding of the European position.
But given the country’s political configuration, the government can’t, of course, defend its position publicly.
I think the real differences in opinions are not as big as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is far from overflowing with enthusiasm about Netanyahu’s policy.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other?
I don’t think it makes things easier for the Germans.
Obviously, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, but today it is not the case.
They cannot therefore fit into a broader political line and must affirm their unique position.
This is what they are currently doing in the euro issue.
In my opinion, Germany will take on a locomotive role in the future and push Europe to adopt a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This question has always been delicate.
But in my opinion, the Germans are well aware that they must play a role that further marks their independence.
Does Germany play a major role on the international stage, does Germany only want to play a key role?
Or is it still difficult to take on leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still uncomfortable for it and, for obvious reasons, the country still has difficulty playing a more important role.
If you look at, for example, the euro crisis, you notice that whenever Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
It doesn't make things easier for the Germans.
In fact, it is always the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
It has to deal with neighbors and opinions very varied, and it is not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European policy is only diminishing, but at the moment, the EU is not filling this gap, so who remains?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant for them and if they're only less appreciated of it, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Washington Transatlantic Academy, an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly analyze the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specialized in German politics, U.S. foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Brand Protection" in China: When Puma and Armani Suddenly Become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are known brands worldwide.
Armani Polo... what is it really about?
Behind this name is a trademark that is officially registered in China, but has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark thus enjoys such protection that the company bearing its name cannot file a complaint.
And even if she could, it's not sure she'd get a win of cause.
“It is becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China,” says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing, who specializes in violating property rights in the Far East.
Every week, a new file comes to my desk.
Imitators only need a few additional letters to register their trademarks.
Thus, instead of Gucci, we record Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we record Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied, such as Puma, the manufacturer of sports goods.
Pattloch opens a workbook containing records made with the Beijing Trademark Office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company registered the Zegna DF Puma brand, a name that the firm artificially created by taking over part of the name of Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is a known fact that the Chinese have become the world champions of copying and intellectual property violation.
In large cities, there are multi-storey shopping centers that sell virtually only counterfeits.
However, the cases of Pattloch are different: his mandates charge him with addressing the fact that the Chinese Trademark Office officially grants Chinese companies the right to use a name that is already protected in another country.
The Chinese are talking about "Bang Mingpai", a parent brand.
The term is derived from "Bang Dakuan".
It is with this term that women who marry wealthy men are designated.
The Chinese authorities say they have nothing to blame.
“It’s bad for business, we have to fight this trend,” demands Pattloch.
“The brand is sweetened, the singularity disappears, the damage to reputation is enormous.”
Financial losses and legal expenses are in millions for the sectors concerned, especially for expensive flagship products.
According to data from the market analysis company CLSA, China represents, with an annual volume of €15 billion, the world’s third largest market for luxury goods and the fastest growing market.
However, it is not easy to delete dubious records from the trademark registry and these procedures are expensive.
The latter can last up to nine years, and the outcome is never certain.
Pattloch reports on the trials in which the court rejected the complaint, because after a long time, the criticized denomination had become a "reality of the market."
Pattloch explains to us that if the complainant is unlucky, he may even be forced to pay money to the plagiarist because he would have harmed his trademark in China.
In this area, it is sometimes the law of the jungle that dominates.
Famous cases also relate to graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal battle against construction machine manufacturer Sany, the same company that had just bought the Putzmeister concrete pump manufacturer.
This is why the Chinese can use an emblem that resembles the Mercedes star.
Geely, the Volvo acquirer, used a blue-and-white logo that reminded us of that of BMW. The conflict was settled and Geely had to modify it.
The fashion house Lacoste had lost against plagiarists in Hong Kong and Singapore who had reoriented the famous crocodile’s gaze in the opposite direction.
According to the Chinese authorities, they are guilty of nothing.
The CTMO brand office in Beijing admits, however, to have experienced some difficulties in 2010 due to a lack of staff and space.
However, last year the office reportedly moved from an "emergency situation in the course of work to a normal recovery".
Thus, the number of untreated opposition proceedings would have decreased by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 such cases would have been closed, which represents a 75% increase compared to the previous year.
Nevertheless, 81,500 proceedings remain pending at the office.
Acting is expensive
As often in China, the figures are impressive.
Last year, OCMW received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
According to the office, this is a record and this means that China is at the top for the tenth consecutive time in the ranking for the number of new deposits in the world.
This would also apply to the total number of legal trademarks, which is 5.5 million.
In 2011, the office reportedly accounted for 1.8 billion yuan of registration fee.
In other words, each recorded an average of 1,280 yuan, or 160 euros.
A legal battle costs much more, as is illustrated in the case of the German family business Freudenberg.
For more than seven years, the company has been fighting against a Chinese plagiarist.
Certainly, the Germans were able to obtain that illegal manufacturing of vehicle components was suspended.
However, the imitator was able to maintain its Chinese rights to the Freudenberg brand.
“It’s our fault because surnames cannot be protected in Germany,” said Hanno Wentzler, CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialties in Munich.
The Trademark Office therefore rejected the Munich people's objection.
Freudenberg certainly won the case in the following two instances, but the opposing side continues to fight to this day.
Vigilance is required
Today, the case is pending in the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident, he believes in a positive outcome of the trial and boasts the professionalism of the judges.
Nevertheless, he adds: "The procedure is long, difficult and costs us a lot of time and money."
Internal costs are also difficult to assess, and the archival department has even had to review the records of the past 100 years in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg even proposed in vain to the opposing party a "large six-digit euro sum" to resolve the dispute.
“That’s what it means for us,” Wentzler says.
The dangers of the Far East even threaten to overflow to Europe.
This would be the case if imitators from this region were to ensure the exploitation of unprotected trademarks.
For example, a Chinese producer wanted to file the name Freudenberg in Germany for a shoe and leather production company.
The company had long abandoned this sector, but it was still able to prevent the deposit.
Wentzler adds: "Watchfulness is required."
Pattloch and him advise German companies to be very cautious in their trade relations with China.
It is not enough, they believe, to rely on international trademark law, foreigners should rather “register everything that is likely to be protected in China,” as Wentzler says.
Otherwise, the costs may be much higher than those of registration.
Indeed, if Freudenberg lost the battle in the last act of his legal drama, the company should pay licensing fees to the opposing party for the use of his own name, as Wentzler explains.
Or we would lose our place in the market segment in question.
