Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most common sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and blennorrhea (or gonorrhea).
Common STIs are HIV, human papilloma virus, genital herpes, or hepatitis.
The lice of the pubis and the scale belong to the parasitic STIs.
Which groups are mainly concerned?
Syphilis and blennorrhagia often appear in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert-Koch Institute estimates that sexual contact between men causes at least four out of five cases of syphilis reported in Germany.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia-related infections, trichomonase, candidiasis (fungal), blennorrhea and human papilloma virus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The rate of HIV spread among heterosexual adults is relatively low in Germany, however, about 20% of new HIV infections are observed within this group.
The rate of chlamydia-related infections is significantly higher in young people than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three-quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
Furthermore, in Germany, human papilloma virus is common among young people.
What is the evolution of the number of infections?
It is not mandatory to report all sexually transmitted diseases.
According to the Robert-Koch Institute, the number of syphilis cases has more than doubled in 10 years: from 1,967 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011.
Since 2007, the number of new HIV infections has declined.
In 2011, there were about 2,700 cases.
This represents a decrease of one tenth compared to the previous year.
What are the symptoms of a sexual illness?
Infectious diseases can cause abscess in the genitals, urinary pain, white loss, lower abdomen pain, as well as the appearance of pimples and warts.
However, they regularly cause no pain or other symptoms and therefore remain hidden.
How to protect yourself?
Condoms may decrease the risk of infection, but they do not protect 100%.
The reason for this is that the pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted through lubricating infection or through close body contacts.
Therefore, experts recommend that anyone who frequently changes sexual partners take regular examinations.
Most rapidly screened STIs can be cured and late sequels can be avoided.
