The journey to the Talysh Mountains is of an arduous romanticism.
Around the many turning points of the road, the small bus cahotes along wooded hills, torrential rivers and modest farms.
Everything is green and fertile, almost like in the Black Forest.
But we are here in the deep south of Azerbaijan, the border with Iran is only a few kilometers away.
This is where the Caucasian ethnic group of the name of Talysh lives, about whom little is known, except that they speak Persian and Azeri perfectly and have a very long life.
Terminus: Lerik.
The small town is flamboyant with its too aggressive Soviet-era architecture that does not match the picturesque mountain landscape at all.
European tourists are rare here, the journey from the capital of Azerbaijan, Baku, is far too painful.
It takes eight hours to travel the 323 kilometers, because the road has only one lane.
The province has not yet taken advantage of the legendary wealth that the country owes to its oil reserves in the Caspian Sea.
However, Pilata Fatulayeva, 48, is convinced that Lerik has the potential to become a tourist place.
“Bakou became famous in May thanks to the Eurovision competition, and next year there will be the festival of the world’s oldest people,” says Fatulayeva.
She is the director of the Museum of Longevity, the only such museum in the world.
There you can discover the lives of about eight dozen Talysh of the region who are over 100 years old. Fatulayeva shows us a black and white photo.
This is my grandfather, he reached the age of 120.
Have a child at 136 years old
But the controversial star of the museum is Şirali Müslümov, a shepherd who would have been 168 years old.
However, there is no birth certificate.
And when one thinks that the oldest documented person was 122 years old, Müslümov's age seems more than doubtful.
"He was born in 1805 in this region, he died in 1973," said Fatulayeva.
The man would have married three times and had 23 children. At the age of 136, he would have still conceived a daughter.
Has Şirali Müslümov been wrong for a few decades by calculating his age?
Rembrandt Scholz, a gerontologist at the Max-Planck Institute in Rostock, also heard of the old man of Central Asia.
“Surprisingly elderly people also live in some parts of China, Japan or the Hunza Valley in Pakistan,” Scholz says, “in Sardinia, too, there are men who live incredibly old.”
However, it is impossible to establish scientific evidence due to the absence of the documents, not to mention that there was no civil record.
Every day, a glass of melted butter
Nevertheless, it is true that people in the Lerik region often reach age worthy of the patriarchs of the Bible.
Currently, 20 people are over 100 years old.
So what is the reason for the longevity in the south of this country?
Farid Mugimzadeh, the Azeri tour guide, explains that the Talysh have particular genes.
On the other hand, Fatulayeva, the director of the museum, thinks it is a matter of food.
However, from a nutritional point of view, it does not seem plausible that the high-calorie meals of the Talysh, who love meat, bread and especially dairy products and many of which drink a glass of melted butter daily, are good for health.
Or is it the simple way of life that preserves the youth of people? In Cengemiran, a tiny village near the town of Lerik, lives Rubaba Mirzayeva.
At the age of 97, she is still relatively young for the region.
Mirzayeva, who claims to have 143 descendants, lives in a modest wooden house, as it is typical to see throughout the Caucasus region.
She sits on the ground next to a bar, whose content she beats tirelessly.
Eight people live here under one roof, among them one of Mirzayeva’s sons and a daughter, who have long been adults.
Two little kids are also wandering in the house.
In the kitchen, tea is prepared for guests served in typical belly-shaped armed glasses.
Mirzayeva’s white teeth are perfectly aligned, and under her scarf hide long braids of a dark blonde that her son proudly reveals to us.
I’ve always washed my hair with milk, and that’s how I never lost them and they kept their color.
"I have never used shampoo," adds Mirzayeva.
Monthly retirement is enough to live
She has always eaten what comes from her own farm: tomatoes, potatoes and peas.
In my entire life, I have never bought any food in a supermarket.
Then she tells us about her husband who was in the army.
The worst times were after World War II.
But everything improved when "beloved father" Heydar Aliyev took over.
The language of propaganda amazes in the mouth of an old lady.
However, the worship of the paternal figure of the nation, a man who ruled his country as a dictator, almost knows no limits in Azerbaijan.
He was in power until 2003, after which his son Ilham succeeded him.
In any case, the elderly in Azerbaijan are not aware of the distress.
Mirzayeva receives 230 manats monthly (about the same amount as in euros) for her retirement, an amount that guarantees a good living in the region.
And perhaps Mirzayeva's long graying son is right: "The elders enjoy great respect in our culture."
They are the center of the great family, they are loved, cared for and happy.
This is a good reason to live as long as possible.
