Bradley Manning did not complain about ill-treatment, prosecutors say.
Prosecutors are trying to counter the claims of ill-treatment that Bradley Manning was allegedly the victim of during the detention.
The trial concerns Manning's detention in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense wants to classify the case on the grounds that Manning's abduction took place under extremely difficult conditions.
The soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to demonstrate Friday that soldier Bradley Manning -- accused of being the cause of the biggest leak of confidential information in the history of the U.S. military -- has missed numerous occasions to complain about the ill-treatment he claims to have undergone during his military detention.
During a cross-examination with Manning, during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Maj. Ashden Fein stated that recordings of weekly visits made to Manning by officers during his nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, revealed no complaints about his treatment.
The counter-examination -- during a hearing, the defence filed a petition demanding that the Manning case be seized on the grounds that the kidnapping was under very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- took place a day after Manning testified to his desire to commit suicide during his detention.
The military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The documents were subsequently published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks never confirmed that Manning was their source.
At the hearing on Friday, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms the officers had filled out after meeting with Manning during his detention in Quantico Military Prison, where he was subjected to maximum prison isolation from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein mentioned the forms Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment his guards gave him was "excellent" and that the treatment he had received in the prison was overall "very professional."
The forms do not report any complaints of ill-treatment, although officers directly questioned him about his treatment in prison, Fein said.
Manning replied that he orally expressed concerns about certain issues and that the officers visited had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would deal with them, but they did not record the issues mentioned.
“They wrote ‘no problem’ (after addressing concerns), and yet that didn’t mean that I hadn’t raised any problems,” Manning said.
Military Judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment during an interview in January 2011 with the special commission that met to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during the meeting was to change his restrictive status indicating a “risk of injury.”
The military said they had assigned him this restrictive status -- a level below close surveillance for suicide risk -- for his protection and the safety of others.
“I wanted the staff to know that I was well, and I wanted to be withdrawn from this status ... in order to benefit from a better quality of life from my point of view,” Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday on his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to military prison from the Marine Corps base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he thought of committing suicide when he was in Kuwait and fainted once because of the heat.
He added that not being kept aware of what was going to happen to him or what was happening in the rest of the world was very anxious.
“My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to this cage,” Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
Once at Quantico, Manning said he had spent most of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours -- without company.
Manning also added that the only objects he had were a mattress, a blanket, tongs, clothes and his glasses.
He tried to stay in motion because sleeping or staying lying during the day was contrary to regulation.
Manning also said that when he was trying to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards didn’t see his face when he turned at night, they would wake him so that they could see his face.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint for Manning's treatments in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge also asked Manning about an allegation reported in his testimony Thursday -- that after being forced to sleep naked for an entire night in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other detainees one morning during the appeal.
Manning testified that at no time was he allowed to cover up with a blanket during the call.
During the judge's questions on Friday, Manning said he had deduced from his guard's order that he should release his blanket that could have hid his nakedness, but he acknowledged that no one had ordered him to release her.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before, as he allegedly tried to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reportedly told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his pant or tongs to hurt himself, but he didn't.
That night, Manning testified that his underwear, tongs, and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will take into account the experiences he experienced during his detention and that he will significantly reduce his sentence if he is to be found guilty in a martial court, a trial that is expected to take place early next year.
The defense said Manning is considering pleading guilty of the least serious crimes and fighting for the abandonment of other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend, with prosecutors who should argue that conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has confirmed that Manning has been incarcerated in accordance with the rules governing the conditions of detention of all inmates in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include theft of public property or documents, collusion with the enemy, resulting in the illegal publication of information on the Internet, and the transmission of national defence information.
If all charges are detained, he shall be sentenced to life in criminal detention.
