After reviewing numerous publications and submitting the idea to a discussion group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as an experiment that consists of "willing to do something but failing to get into a satisfactory activity."
What differentiates boredom from apathy, he says, is that the person is not undertaking a task even though he would like it.
With apathy, he said, there is no desire to do anything.
What is at the heart of the boredom, he said, is “the interruption of the attention process, associated with a bad mood and the feeling that time is passing slowly.”
Boring can look like a depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that while both can be linked, boring people tend to think the problem comes from the environment or the world, while depressed people think the problem comes from them.
Sometimes we think we get bored when it is actually a problem of concentration.
As part of their study, "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", which was published in the newspaper "Perspectives on Psychological Science" in September, Professor Eastwood and colleagues highlighted an older experience in which participants listened on tape, the voice of a person reading a magazine article.
Some bands heard, coming from the next room, the too loud sound of a TV show that had no reports, others just heard the TV show, and the third group did not hear the soundtrack at all.
Those who heard low-noise TV said they were more bored than the other two groups - they struggled to concentrate, but didn't know why, and attributed this concentration problem to boredom.
When you’re trying to focus on a challenging or engaging task, an attention disruption can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, an associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study’s authors.
On the other hand, when you do a boring task, "like watching objects on a editing line, music can help you not get bored."
In fact, he says, now we know that when you twist or scratch, these gestures, often seen as signs of boredom, are actually a good way to stay more physically alert.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to snorkel learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to stay without moving," said Professor Fenske.
We all get bored one day or another - the delay of my plane flight, a speaker with a single-corded voice, a particularly boring film.
But some people are more likely to get bored than others.
To measure this, researchers developed a “Body Predisposition Scale” in the 1980s.
The scale includes statements like, "Among the tasks I perform, many of them are repetitive and monotone," and "I have so many interests that I don't have time to do everything."
Using such a scale, researchers found that boys tend to get bored more often than girls, said Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, and in particular need numerous and varied stimulations.
But in general, teenagers are quickly blased.
In 1991, Reed Larson, an individual and community development professor at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day via a beeper.
He noted that 32 percent of teenagers said they were bored at school and during homework, while 23 percent said they were bored when they were not at school.
On the other hand, 3% of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he didn’t know whether today’s boredom percentages, 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But he added that he knew that “adolescence is a time when boredom reaches its highest level,” especially because children and adolescents don’t have much control over what they want to do.
If I rest my question: is boring good for you?
Sometimes no, because in its extreme form, it can lead people to take absurd physical risks, bet or abuse certain substances to spend time, as studies show.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers evoke a link between boredom and creativity, said Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying the problem for more than two decades.
“Borry is the way the brain has found to let you know that you should do something else,” said Gary Marcus, a psychology professor at the N.Y.U.
But the brain doesn’t always know what is the most appropriate thing to do.
If you get bored and use this energy to play guitar and cook, it will make you happy.
But if you watch TV, it will make you happy in the short term, but not in the long term.
So if your child gets bored and you give him an iPad, he will not get bored anymore, but he will not have learned to take care of himself or self-regulation, says Professor Fenske.
And "this self-regulation moves from one situation to another," he says.
Not only does your child learn to entertain, they get more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should glorify boredom.
Just as I don’t think we should criticize it either.
Feeling comfortable outside of the constant bubbling that activities and technology generate is the goal to which we should tend.
Professor Eastwood agrees on this point.
“We need to get bored more often, but boring arouses an acute and frenetic desire to be connected to something that makes sense,” he said.
According to him, what people are looking for is a way to disconnect and enjoy downtime.
“In an environment where we are constantly hyperstimulated,” he added, “it is difficult to find ways to get into something when the noise stops.”
