For four euros, the Indonesian volcano carriers risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through the steep stone trails.
There are people for whom work is a hell and others who work literally in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn a living carrying sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
It must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where sulphur gas emanating from the earth's entrails solidifies at contact with air.
After harvesting large sulfur rocks, which weigh almost 70 kilos in total, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the steep trails.
There are only 250 meters to the summit of the volcano that culminates at 2,386 meters, but exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb this distance, at a turtle-look, keeping the balance and measuring their footsteps so as not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a wrong step could cost their lives, as it happened to a French tourist who made a deadly fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents of euro for every kilo of sulfur extracted.
