This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, it can be said, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) per kilogram of sulfur.
It then sells it at 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to the petrochemical industry since this ore is very present in everyday life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to whiten sugar.
"As we carry about 70 pounds, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) each trip," explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
Each takes him 3 hours and he ends up exhausted, but this allows him to earn 138,000 rupees (11.50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems to be a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is three times what it would earn in the fields.
“The income of miners is very high here, where the harvest of coffee is paid 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros) per day and where the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros),” says the bearer who once worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, her salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) per day and the job was not as difficult, but Anto returned close to her family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as sulfur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I have married them to l'Islam.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, constantly coughs and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
