Singapore is a rich and high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and its strict social controls.
Singapore's birth rate, according to its national population distribution, is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it found itself above 2, considered the renewal rate was in 1976.
Why do Singaporeans have no more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of marriage and family policies at the National Population Division, says this is due to “better education” and “a broader choice of career opportunities.”
“This has allowed people to have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond marriage and the constitution of a family,” she explains.
These changes in social standards have contributed to an increase in the number of singles and delayed marriage and births, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at radically increasing immigration to counter population decline has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, websites abound with barely disguised xenophobia against new immigrants, especially Chinese who are accused of getting wages down and not integrating.
The rise in immigration is also perceived as one of the reasons why the party in place in Singapore saw its worst electoral outcomes last year since independence.
Since the elections, they have been trying to fix the problem with the introduction of higher quotas and taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the fall in the birth rate has known effects on a country's economic growth, tax income, health costs and immigration policies, the example of Singapore also has unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to avoid the construction of many small houses.
For example, it started to affect the real estate sector.
Urban development authorities have begun to control the number of small apartments, known as the "shoe box", which can be built in specific areas of the city.
