However, the authorities are concerned that they can promote a single lifestyle and discourage promoters wishing to build large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, managing director of real estate company EL Developers, says that its “shoe boxes” sell much faster than larger housing.
They are more popular, in the sense that these homes are built much faster than those of larger size.
For this reason, it is much more profitable for our cash.
However, he admits that the new standards give clearer instructions to promoters, who were previously put sticks in the wheels if they wanted to offer too many small housing in a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
If so long these new regulations can be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, by discussing with Singaporeans working in the center's financial district, it would seem that they won't have much effect.
“People are very stressed, homes are expensive, just like education, that’s why people put it back to later,” says a young executive.
Other people can have children.
“But for me, it’s important to have my money and my time,” another 20-year-old declares.
Men and women mention their careers, stress, and the cost of access to property and education as reasons preventing them from having children.
Thus, although the government is trying to convince its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, it is the Singaporeans themselves who have the last word.
What is private offline is private online
