UNASUR Summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The sixth Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the seven present presidents.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the Sixth Ordinary Meeting of the Heads of State and Government of the Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially reported that it would be disclosed after the closure of the summit, and then claimed that it would be published from time to time on the website of the Peruvian government.
When questioned on the text, they reported that the content of the text had been presented by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, in brief statements to the press.
The access of journalists to information about the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private, restricted audio session" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information circulated among the journalists was given by press officials from some of the Unasur governments attending the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more important information.
Later, the Peruvian presidency sent an email to the media with the "final statement" of the summit, but it was President Humala's speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
In October, Peru hosted the 3rd South America Summit (ASPA) and, on that occasion, although this was requested by the press, it did not broadcast the declaration also called the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official website of the ASPA, it is possible to verify that the document was published last March.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to put in place safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited the obtaining of information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement between Chile and Peru to accept a judgment by the Court of The Hague ruling a different border between the two countries.
Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the ICJ’s decision to hear both sides’ pleas in the Lima trial against Santiago that begins Monday in The Hague.
“We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes we are holding today before this international court,” President Humala said, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
“Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of international controversies, treaties and courts,” Piñera said in a statement.
The confirmation by the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia this week denounced the Bogota Pact by which it agreed to submit to the decisions of that international tribunal, after a decision on maritime borders with Nicaragua that it considered seriously erroneous.
The summit took place without the presence of Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from the Unasur since 2011 after the dismissal of its former president Fernando Lugo, has not participated in the appointment.
Host President Ollanta Humala was in charge of opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The mandatary read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the action lines of 31 projects had been set between South American countries for a total of $17 million in investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the countries of the Unasur would make "important steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits".
He informed that actions would be put in place to "improve cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions for better access to drugs, low-cost internet access throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters."
With a Europe in crisis, “economic consolidation (of Latin America) should not have a triumphalist matrix but must help increase our productive matrix and envision a better future for our people,” concluded President Humala.
“We have decided to privilege a group of 31 iconic projects that improve the connection of South America’s spaces, especially in rural and border areas ... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits,” the Peruvian president said in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five were concerned with Peru and were on the transverse axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two were aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not provide any further details.
Similarly, the final document mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that this country's electoral process will enable its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and having good relations with its neighbours, is another theme addressed at the summit.
In that sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his counterpart from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico City to calmly discuss the maritime dispute through a judgment of the ICJ requested by Bogota.
“It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I will have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega,” Santos said.
“We are going to revise all these pathways, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua that will ask for a discussion with this country,” he said.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will resolve this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," Santos said.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico City where they plan to attend the takeover of power of the country's new president, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Similarly, as part of the summit, the bloc’s defence ministers will meet in advance to approve the 2013 Plan of Action, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus in terms of defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are part of the Unasur, although the latter country is suspended.
Peru assumes the pro temporary presidency of the regional bloc.
