Death of actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth, Texas, became known worldwide by the leading role of John Ross Ewing, better known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he played a scrupulous, fearsome and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as the unscrupulous oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year in the role of J.R in a new season of Dallas, died Friday night of cancer complications, according to a family statement sent to The Associate Press for Warner Bros., production house of Dallas.
“Larry was back in his dear hometown of Dallas, playing again the ironic role he loved most,” the family said.
Larry’s family and close friends were with him in Dallas on that Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played his wife's role in the original and subsequent series, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, his press attorney, Jeffrey Lane, said.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented, and I will miss him a lot.
“He was an exceptional person and he lived life fully,” Gray said in a statement.
Doctors had diagnosed liver cirrhosis with Larry Hagman in 1992 and he had acknowledged having drunk a lot for many years.
In 1995, he had been detected with a malignant liver tumor and had undergone a transplant.
Several years before "Dallas", Hagman made himself known on television as an ordinary guy in the series "Jinny of my dreams" broadcast by NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In this, he played the role of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered a seductive genius, played by Barbara Eden, and brought her home.
He also played in two comedies that stayed shortly on the antenna, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
Among his roles in the cinema are well-received roles by critics in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was thanks to his masterful interpretation of the delightfully disgusting J.R. that Larry Hagman had his greatest success.
The CBS drama series on the Ewing clan and their loved ones was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan "Who killed J.R.?", invented to maintain the suspense around an episode full of emotions in which Hagman's character is almost murdered, has generated speculation around the world and millions of dollars played in bets.
Thanks to this, among other things, the series reached a record audience at that time.
When the response was revealed in a November 1980 episode, 41 million viewers were on average in front of their screen and made "Dallas" the second most watched entertainment program in the world, after the final episode of "MASH" in 1983, which had gathered 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law Kristin (interpreted by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. had made her pregnant and then threatened to accuse her of prostitution if she did not leave the city, but others also had reasons to assault her.
Hagman played the role of Ewing as a corrupt and insatiable man but with a charismatic smile: a dishonest entrepreneur and an unfaithful husband who tried to interne his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray).
"I know what it would take as an epitaph for J.R," Hagman said in 1988.
We should write, "Ci-Git the Honest Citizen J.R. Ewing."
Here's the only part he's lost.
Victoria Principal, co-protagonist of the original series, recalled Hagman on Friday as a “immense man, both on the small screen and in life.”
It is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of each of us, who have been lucky enough to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were broadcast a few months ago with great success on the TNT channel.
The recording of five episodes is already finished for the second season and a sixth is underway, the channel informed.
For now, neither Warner nor TNT have announced how Hagman's death will be included in the series.
