A course about the "End of the World" has just begun
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and global warming.
This semester, when Religion Professor Stuart Charmé decided to give a lesson on the end of the world, he knew he was throwing an irresistible hook there: the end of the Mayan calendar "big count" on December 21, which many refer to as proof of the imminent end of the world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea what was waiting for him in the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a fiscal gap that some have nicknamed “the Armageddon of Debt,” and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where late-time Christian theorists thought the apocalypse would be triggered.
“I didn’t realize that this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I’ve ever known,” Charmé told his students at Rutgers-Camden University, New Jersey, this week.
If we look at what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we were telling it, it was a very good time.
And we must remember that what is bad is good for those who believe in the apocalypse.
And he's not the only teacher to give lessons on "the end of the world" this semester, which will, in theory, be the last in history.
At Temple, Deputy Professor Barry Vacker gives the class "Media, Culture and End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and global warming.
"We are analyzing this because these ideas proliferate over time," he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides some human behavior.
If nuclear weapons were to fall into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with real-life examples.
“I tried to inform my students about what was possible, likely, credible, and impossible,” Vacker said.
On the main campus of the Pennsylvania State University, Latin American History Professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply entitled "The End of the World".
“We’re adding ‘2012’ to have the opportunity to give the class again, in case the world doesn’t disappear,” Professor Restall said.
Despite the "imminent disaster", students must study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final exam will be passed the day before the Apocalypse, which leaves students no choice but to work "until the very night of the supposed end of the world," Restall said.
The classes proved quite popular.
"It was complete in two hours," Restall said about his high-level student course, composed of 35 students.
We received emails several weeks before the start of the semester from people asking if there was still room.
Students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“It fascinates me to see what people are able to do to comfort themselves,” says Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student of religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers-Camden University.
For the fear of the Apocalypse, whether secular or religious, is only a matter of comfort, or absence of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student of Psychology and Nursing, claims to have watched all the apocalyptic films.
"I had never heard of a class teaching this subject," he said.
I appreciate it.
But none of the students surveyed, let alone a teacher, told us to believe in the end date of the world on December 21.
"Our first project was about Mayan prophecy, and in some ways we have discredited it," says Julie Zegle, a 21-year-old senior student at Temple, from West Chester.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world, it’s just a key date on the calendar, Restall said.
But I acknowledge that there is an anxiety related to the apocalypse in Western culture, dating back centuries, which causes people to react to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused a rise in these speculations.
“In other parts of the globe, people don’t think about that,” he said.
This is mostly from the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who teaches in the Philippines this year, responded quickly when asked if he knew we were teaching here on "the end of the world".
"The Philippines are not participating in the end of the world," he replied, as if it were an exception from a higher authority.
We have a grace from the Pope.
Restall notes that over the years, we have talked about the many supposed dates of the last judgment, and he says that if nothing happens on December 21st, “people will immediately start thinking about the next date” or philosophy that December 21st marks the beginning of a 7-year period at the end of which the world will disappear.
Students and teachers take the date lightly.
Many have told us that they plan to go to "the end of the world" holidays.
“Sometimes I call friends and we laugh about them together,” said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
